        {
          "id": 73402,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Papillitis </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 73403,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Retrobulbar neuritis </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 73404,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Toxic optic neuropathy </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 73405,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Papilledema</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 42-year-old female patient came to the ophthalmologist with complaints of sudden loss of vision in the left eye, associated with painful ocular movements. On fundoscopy, everything appeared normal. What is the probable diagnosis?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4422912",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31453,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        8
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B)&nbsp; Retrobulbar neuritis </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The given scenario is suggestive of <strong>RETROBULBAR NEURITIS</strong>. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Retrobulbar neuritis is characterized by <strong>normal appearance of optic disc</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">It is classically described as a condition in which neither the patient nor the ophthalmologist sees anything.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">It is the <strong>most common type in adults</strong> and is frequently <strong>associated with multiple sclerosis</strong> (MS).</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Papillitis is the most common type of optic neuritis in children. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Neuroretinitis is the least common type of optic neuritis.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">. <strong>Papillitis</strong>: This is <strong>inflammation of the optic nerve head</strong> which can cause similar symptoms but would usually show abnormalities (like disc swelling) on <strong>fundoscopy</strong>. Common <strong>causes</strong> incluse <strong>Arteritic and Non-arteritic ischaemic Optic Neuropathy and Diabetic Papillopathy</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">. <strong>Toxic Optic Neuropathy</strong>: This typically <strong>presents as a gradual, painless vision loss, often affecting both eyes</strong>, and is <strong>associated with exposure to certain toxins</strong> or <strong>nutritional deficiencies</strong>. It does not typically present with pain on eye movement.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">. <strong>Papilledema</strong>: This is <strong>swelling of the optic disc</strong> due to <strong>increased intracranial pressure</strong>. While it can <strong>affect vision, it is usually not associated with pain on eye movement</strong> and would be visible on fundoscopy as optic disc swelling.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The presentation of sudden vision loss with painful eye movements and a normal optic disc on examination is characteristic of retrobulbar neuritis.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective</span></u></strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: </span></u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Diagnose <strong>retrobulbar neuritis</strong> in a <strong>patient presenting with sudden vision loss</strong>, <strong>painful eye movements</strong>, and a <strong>normal optic disc on fundoscopy</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><u>REF</u>:&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">KANSKI 9<sup>TH</sup> EDITION PAGE 754</span></strong></span></span></p>",
