      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B) Optic neuritis</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Causes of <strong>Acquired Colour Blindness</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">RED GREEN defects</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> = <strong>papillitis</strong></span></span></span>\r\n\r\n\t<ul style=\"list-style-type:circle\">\r\n\t\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Optic neuritis</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Toxic optic neuropathy</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Stargadt disease</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t</ul>\r\n\t</li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">BLUE defect&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">(Blue blindness) = <strong>old age</strong></span></span></span>\r\n\t<ul style=\"list-style-type:circle\">\r\n\t\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Due to <strong>increased sclerosis of the crystalline lens</strong>, there is <strong>physical absorption of the blue rays</strong> by the <strong>increased amber coloured pigment</strong> in the <strong>nucleus</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t</ul>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A: Retinal detachment</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: While <strong>serious and can lead to permanent vision loss</strong>, <strong>retinal detachment does not typically cause red-green color blindness</strong>. Symptoms usually include floaters, flashes of light, and a shadow or curtain effect over part of the visual field.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C: Central serous retinopathy</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: This condition <strong>involves fluid buildup under the retina but doesn&#39;t usually result in red-green color blindness</strong>. Symptoms typically include distorted and blurred central vision.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D: Glaucoma</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: This is a group of <strong>eye conditions that damage the optic nerve, usually due to high eye pressure.</strong> It primarily affects peripheral vision initially and can lead to tunnel vision in advanced stages, but it does not typically cause red-green color blindness.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective</span></u></strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: </span></u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Understanding that while <strong>optic neuritis can alter color perception</strong>, <strong>classical red-green color blindness is genetic</strong> and <strong>not typically a symptom of common eye diseases</strong> like <strong>retinal detachment</strong>, central serous retinopathy, or glaucoma.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><u>Ref</u>:&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">pg 294/ Anatomy and physiology of eye/ AK KHURANA/ 3<sup>rd</sup> edition</span></strong></span></span></p>",
